{{Distinguish|African Studies Association}} The '''African Studies Association of the United Kingdom''' ('''ASAUK''') formed in 1963 "to advance [[African studies]], particularly in the United Kingdom, by providing facilities for the interchange of information and ideas and the co-ordination of activities by and between persons and institutions concerned with the study of Africa."<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[African Affairs]] |title=African Studies Association of the United Kingdom |year= 1964 |volume=63 |jstor=719763 }}</ref> [[Antony Nicholas Allott|Antony Allott]] and [[Roland Oliver]] led the founding of the group.<ref>{{cite journal |title=British African Studies since the Second World War: A Personal Account |author=[[John Donnelly Fage]] |journal= African Affairs |volume= 88 |year= 1989 |jstor=722694 }}</ref>[http://researcharchive.vuw.ac.nz/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10063/941/thesis.pdf] In recent times the [[Royal African Society]] administers the association.
The group organizes conferences and runs the Standing Committee on University Studies in Africa[https://web.archive.org/web/20030824151350/http://www.asauk.net/] and the Standing Conference on Library Materials on Africa.[http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n79081456/]
==Presidents== {{col-list|colwidth=22em| * 1963 to 1964: [[Margery Perham]] (inaugural president) * 1964 to 1965: [[Audrey Richards]] * {{circa}} 1964: A.F. Robertson * 1966 to 1967: [[Roland Oliver]] * 1969 to 1970: [[Antony Nicholas Allott|Antony Allott]] * 1978 to 1979: [[Shula Marks]] * 1980 to 1982: [[Terence Ranger]] * c. 1985: David Birmingham * 1988 to 1990: [[Anthony Kirk-Greene]] * 1990 to 1992: [[John McCracken (historian)|John McCracken]] * 1992 to 1994: Christopher Clapham * 1996 to 1998: [[Richard Hodder-Williams]] * 1998 to 2000: JDY Peel * 2000 to 2002: [[Karin Barber]] * 2002 to 2004: Nici Nelson * 2004 to 2006: Graham Furniss * 2006 to 2008: Tunde Zack-Williams * 2008 to 2010: [[William Beinart]] * 2010 to 2012: [[Megan Vaughan]] * 2012 to 2014: Stephanie Newell * 2014 to 2016: [[David Maxwell (historian)|David Maxwell]] * 2016 to 2018: Insa Nolte }}
==Distinguished Africanist award== The ASAUK "Distinguished Africanist" award was established in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=ASAUK Distinguished Africanist Award|url=http://www.asauk.net/news/awards/asauk-distinguished-africanist-award/|publisher=African Studies Association of the United Kingdom|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref> Its recipients have been: {{col-list|colwidth=22em| *2001: [[Basil Davidson]], [[John Fage]], and [[Douglas Rimmer]] *2002: [[Lionel Cliffe]], [[Eldred D. Jones]], [[Marjorie Jones]], and [[Shula Marks]] *2004: [[Roland Oliver]] and [[Terrence Ranger]] *2005: [[Anthony Kirk-Greene]] *2006: [[John Lonsdale (historian)|John Lonsdale]] *2007: [[George Shepperson]] *2008: [[John McCracken (historian)|John McCracken]] *2009: [[James Currey]] *2010: [[Robin Law]] *2011-12: [[Kenneth King (academic)|Kenneth King]], [[Pravina King]], and [[Lalage Bown]] *2013-14: [[Gavin Williams (historian)|Gavin Williams]] *2015-16: [[JDY Peel]], [[Nici Nelson]], and [[Richard Hodder-Williams]] }}
==Bibliography== ;issued by ASAUK * {{citation |title=African Research & Documentation |issn=0305-862X }} 1973-
==References== {{reflist}}
