{{use dmy dates|date=June 2014}} {{use list-defined references|date=June 2014}} {{Use British English|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox goat breed | name = Ciociara Grigia | image = | image_size = 280px | image_alt = | image_caption = | status = {{nobreak|[[FAO]] (2007): endangered<ref name=barb/>}} | altname =Grigia Ciociara | nickname = | country = Italy | distribution = {{unbulleted list|[[Province of Frosinone]]|[[Province of Rome]]}} | standard = [http://www.assonapa.it/norme_ecc/CAPRINI-RA_Standard_WEB/Capra%20Grigia%20Ciociara.htm MIPAAF] | use = milk<ref name=dad/> | maleweight = 75–85 kg<ref name=bigi/> | femaleweight = 45–55 kg<ref name=bigi/> | maleheight = | femaleheight = | type = | skincolor = | woolcolor = | facecolor = | horns = horned or hornless in both sexes | note = }} The '''Ciociara Grigia''' or '''Grigia Ciociara''' is an indigenous [[breed]] of [[goat|domestic goat]] from [[Lazio]] in central Italy. It takes its name from the [[Ciociaria]], the area around [[Frosinone]]. It is thought to have originated in the area of the [[Monti Aurunci]] and the [[Monti Ausoni]].<ref name=aspa3/> It is raised in those mountains, in the [[Monti Lepini]], and in the [[Val Comino]]. Because of the [[transhumant]] management of the herds it has also diffused into some neighbouring areas of [[Campania]] and [[Abruzzo]].<ref name=bigi/> It is one of the forty-three autochthonous Italian goat breeds of limited distribution for which a herdbook is kept by the [[Associazione Nazionale della Pastorizia]], the Italian national association of sheep- and goat-breeders.<ref name=dm/>
At the end of 2013 the registered population was 674.<ref name=aspa2/>
